      <h2>Glossary of Windstorm Terms</h2>
      <p>Below you will find definitions and explanations of common terms used when discussing windstorms.</p>

      <dl class="glossary-list">
        <dt>Windstorm</dt>
        <dd>A storm that is strong enough to cause at least light damage to trees and buildings, and may or may not be accompanied by precipitation. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}</dd>

        <dt>Downburst</dt>
        <dd>A powerful downdraft arising from a thunderstorm or convective cell that hits the ground and spreads out in all directions, capable of producing damaging straight-line winds. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}</dd>

        <dt>Outflow Boundary (Gust Front)</dt>
        <dd>A storm-scale or mesoscale boundary formed between thunderstorm-cooled air (outflow) and the surrounding air. These can trigger additional storms and often produce a sudden wind shift. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}</dd>

        <dt>Haboob</dt>
        <dd>An intense dust storm generated by strong winds from weather fronts or downdrafts of thunderstorms, typically occurring in arid or semi-arid regions. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}</dd>

